ould give minimum weight.\n   110→\n   111→  // Wait - the key insight for MITM minimum weight:\n   112→  // We want min weight of (leftState XOR rightDelta).\n   113→  // This equals: for each bit pattern in {0,1}^cols, count bits.\n   114→  // Approach: sort left states by their \"profile\" to enable fast lookup.\n   115→  // But this still requires O(2^n) total work.\n   116→\n   117→  // For this problem, a practical solution: enumerate one half, store ALL states.\n   118→  // Enumerate other half, for each compute the XOR with the particular solution\n   119→  // and find if any left state makes minimum weight.\n   120→  // But this is O(2^half * leftMapSize) in worst case.\n   121→\n   122→  // PRACTICAL APPROACH for up to 40 free vars:\n   123→  // Split into halves of ~20. Left: 1M states. Right: 1M states.\n   124→  // For each right state r, we want min weight of (l XOR r) over all l in left.\n   125→  // We can't do this efficiently without additional structure.\n   126→\n   127→  // Instead, let's just enumerate ALL combinations in batches.\n   128→  // With numFree <= 40 and needing minimum weight, we use:\n   129→  // Enumerate right half (2^20 = 1M combinations), for each rightDelta:\n   130→  //   Look up in leftMap: we want the leftState that, XOR'd with rightDelta, is minimum weight.\n   131→  //   This is equivalent to finding minimum weight vector in {leftStates XOR rightDelta}.\n   132→  //   We can precompute leftStates sorted or indexed by bit patterns for fast lookup.\n   133→\n   134→  // SIMPLEST CORRECT APPROACH: enumerate both halves, for each right combination,\n   135→  // enumerate all left combinations. This is 2^numFree total = too slow for large numFree.\n   136→\n   137→  // SOLUTION: Accept that this edge case (many free variables) means many buttons with\n   138→  // identical effects. In that case:\n   139→  // - If xp has weight 0 (all zeros solution exists), return [].\n   140→  // - Otherwise, we can use Gray code enumeration